ion and its forensic signature, along with the relevant compliance rule. I'll implement an interactive form with dropdowns to assign reviewers, update status, and manage severity and due date, including an \"Apply Changes\" button. Finally, a local timeline of actions for each item will also be presented.\n\n\n**Verifying Dependencies & Structure**\n\nI've confirmed `lucide-react` is used in the codebase, so those icons are available. Though considering reusability, I've concluded local components are best for fine-grained layout and design consistency, avoiding dependency problems. I'm focusing on mock item design now, preparing a series of 6-8 comprehensive items across client, project, and agent scopes to validate the design. I've started building the first critical item, \"Unsigned kernel module execution,\" with details on scope, severity, and status.\n\n\n**Populating Governance Items**\n\nI'm now detailing some sample governance items. I've designed several initial entries, including \"Unsigned kernel module execution,\" and will create more examples to cover scope, severity, and status. I've worked on the first item, described as a high alert, which involves malicious code trying to hook into the host virtual machine kernel and a corresponding security sandbox alert. The information provided will include a timestamp, compliance rule, and hash for detailed forensic analysis. A second example, a high-severity alert, now describes an enclave isolation boundary warning with telemetry leakage, including scope details, owner, reviewer, status, due date, and relevant compliance.\n\n\n**Expanding Governance Items**\n\nI've crafted two more example governance items to enrich the existing dataset. I've designed a Medium item involving a rejected microservice call with a validated token replacement, including its owner, reviewer, compliance rule, status, and due date. I also created a Low item detailing a stale HSM key rotation with client scope. The design includes scopes, owners, reviewers, status, due dates, timestamps, compliance rules, and hashes. I have now made a high item about cognitive agent drift.\n\n\n\n**Adding Governance Items**\n\nI've added two new items. First is a high severity alert, describing how an inference loop has drifted. The second is a medium entry detailing an audit log mismatch. Both items have specific scopes, owners, reviewers, statuses, and due dates. I've included relevant descriptions, timestamps, compliance rules, and hashes for each, to expand and validate the design. I've also added these to existing examples.\n\n\n**Implementing State Management**\n\nI'm now focusing on state management for the governance items. My plan is to ensure the list is fully state-driven, using React's `useState` hook for updates when a user modifies details and clicks \"Apply Changes\". I'll also implement a dismissible toast notification to confirm local updates, detailing which fields have been changed. I'm keeping the UI design rules in mind to maintain quality.\n\n\n**Designing Visual Hero**\n\nI'm now detailing visual improvements. I plan a unique hero: an SVG-based \"Live Guardrail Grid,\" pulsing or interactive at the top right, or a sleek 3D SVG grid showing active agent enclaves with risk bubbles. Backgrounds will be dark with ultra-thin white borders and high-contrast text. I'll maintain excellent typography using a mix of fonts.\n\n\n"}}
