{"ts":"2026-06-27T07:52:34.229Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing the structure**\n\nI'm starting to get a clear picture! I see how the models function and the way things are working. I need to delve deeper into `lib/mock-data-model.ts`, to look for other imported models. This is perfect for the user's request. My focus remains on the `/admin/governance` build.\n\n\n**Designing the state-based dataset**\n\nI'm developing a state-based dataset in `/app/admin/governance/page.tsx` for granular control. I'll import `previewClientAccounts`, `previewProjects`, and `previewAgentOperations` from `@/lib/mock-data-model` to ensure accurate client, project, and agent integration. The layout design and execution path are next on my agenda, with the focus on the executive security panel of GFF AI.\n\n\n**Visualizing the anomalies**\n\nI'm now focusing on visualizing anomalies across clients, projects, and agents. I've conceived of a \"Deep Enclave Inspection Grid\" as the visual metaphor. It's a dynamic cockpit with subatomic metrics and high-precision status lights. It has a split layout for detailed, local analysis.\n\nI'm developing a layout strategy: A breadcrumb header, quick KPI tiles, and a regulatory disclaimer callout. The core grid will feature a multi-stage filter bar and a card grid.\n\n\n**Refining the Interaction Design**\n\nI'm now honing the interactive features. High-density cards will present governance violations, complete with custom icons and action indicators. Clicking triggers a slide-over detail drawer, revealing compliance rules, payload hashes, and system states. I'll include interactive controls within the drawer for local actions: assigning reviewers, changing severity, and updating status. I'm focusing on smooth transitions, dynamic counter badges, and form-based updates for a fluid user experience.\n\n\n"}}
